Reading devices and habits by Antonina Nesterenko

Univariate Plots Section

Let me introduce the data set.

Citation:

The PSRAI January 2014 Omnibus Week 1 obtained telephone interviews with a nationally representative sample of 1,005 adults living in the continental United States. Telephone interviews were conducted by landline (500) and cell phone (505, including 268 without a landline phone). The survey was conducted by Princeton Survey Research Associates International (PSRAI). …

This omnibus survey contains questions about reading, e-reading, and various electronic devices.

source: http://www.pewinternet.org/datasets/january-2014-e-reading-and-gadgets-omnibus/

Let us look on the histogram of the number of books, readed for the last 12 month:

Distribution in skewed and obscured by the first bar - 0 books, and that is the most frequent number of books, readed by respondents of the survey (!) So I will try to figure out something more interesting from the plot, with log10-transformed x-axis:

A little better - 0 value vanished and we can see more clearly, that among those, who read some books, 3 is the most popular amount. Also, we can see, that, as it is hard to tell for sure, multipliers of 5 - 5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 50 are more usual answers.

NOTE: 97 means “97 or more”.

Later we will slice this data by the levels of other variables to answer a questions like: what kind of people read 0 books? Young or order? Maybe, education level is playing part? Do people with children read books to them? Do those, who have electronic devises for reading read more books?

For now, I want to investigate individual variables more.

How many respondents have an electronic devices?

93% has, ~ 6% doesn’t have a cell phone.

And how many smartphones among those cell phones?

54% smartphones, ~ 40% stupidphones.
76% has, ~ 22% doesn’t have a computer or laptop.
32% has, ~ 67% doesn’t have a device made primarily for e-book reading.
42% has, ~ 58% doesn’t have a tablet computer.

Distribution of ages:

the same, devided by groups:

Most people are adults in their 49 - 64.

NOTE: minimal age of respondent is 18 years.

Races:

Whites are the most represented group.

Education level:

Most respondents have completed education, high school graduates are most numerous (~ 27%)

Income:

Most respondents refused to report their income; distribution looks “bimodal” - two distinct groups are $20,000 - $30,000 and $50,000 - $75,000 of yearly income.

Employment:

Almost 50 - 50: half of the respondents are fully or partly employed, half - unemployed.

Gender:

48% males, 52% females.

How many of them are parents?

~24% have children, ~78% don’t have children.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1005 observations in the dataset - answers of the 1005 U.S. residents to the set of questions (results of the poll) concerning reading of books. 21 of 23 choosen variables are categorical (factors) and 2 - n_readed (number of books read in the last 12 month) and age are integer.

Factor variables include:

has_cellph (does respondent have cell phone) - yes, no, don’t know, refused

has_comp (does respondent have a computer or laptop) - yes, no, refused

has_ereder (does respondent have a device made primarily for e-book reading) - yes, no, don’t know, refused

has_tables (does respondent have a tablet computer) - yes, no, don’t know, refused

is_smart (is respondent’s cell phone in smartphone) - yes, no, don’t know, refused

r_printedb (were any of books read in the last 12 month printed books) - yes, no, don’t know, refused

r_audiob (were any of books read in the last 12 month audiobooks) - yes, no, don’t know

r_ebook (were any of books read in the last 12 month e-books) - yes, no, don’t know

r_eb_tablet (how often does respondent read e-books on a tablet computer) - e_day (every day), ft_week (few times a week), ft_mo (few time a month), less (less often then previous), not_dev (do not read e-books on this device)

r_ed_ereader (how often does respondent read e-books on a device made primarily for e-book reading) - levels are same as in r_eb_tablet

r_ed_com (how often does respondent read e-books on a computer or laptop) - levels are same as in r_eb_tablet

r_ed_cellph (how often does respondent read e-books on a cell phone) - levels are same as in r_eb_tablet

r_yesterday (did respondent read book yesterday) - yes, no

employ (employment of the respondent) - f_time (full time employed), p_time (part time employed), not(unemployed), refused

parent (does respondent a parent) - yes, no

gender - male, female

educ (education level of the respondent) - ordered factor - from top to buttom > . > . > … > .:

lt_hs = Less than high school (Grades 1-8 or no formal schooling)

hs_incom = High school incomplete (Grades 9-11 or Grade 12 with NO diploma)

hs_grad = High school graduate (Grade 12 with diploma or GED certificate)

col_no_deg = Some college, no degree (includes community college)

as_deg = Two year associate degree from a college or university

bach = Four year college or university degree/Bachelor’s degree (e.g., BS, BA, AB)

postgrad_no_deg = Some postgraduate or professional schooling, no postgraduate degree

postgrad = Postgraduate or professional degree, including master’s, doctorate, medical or law degree (e.g., MA, MS, PhD, MD, JD)

race - white, black, asian, mixed, indian, other, refused

income - ordered factor - less than $10,000 a year < $10,000 - $20,000 a year < …< more than $150,000 a year, refused

some observations:

Median number of books, read in the last 12 month is 5, though most respondents didn’t read a books in last 12 month at all,

most respondents have cell phone, though only 54% of them - smartphones. And some (maybe elderly) people can’t distinguish smartphones,

people still read printed books! - 92% of respondents, who read at least one book, read at least one printed book,

respondents, who have a device, made primarily for e-book reading, more likely to read books every day.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features are number of books readed and frequency of reading books. I will try to investigate, what factor variables contribute to main features. For now I suspect, that having a special device increase number of read books, but what about printed books? Maybe, age?

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your

investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Parenthood, education, employment and income may be assossiated with the reading habits.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I made age “buckets” to represent stages of life (to made associations more clear, to use this feature for coloring of plots, …)

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?

Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change

the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

While wrangling the data I renamed variables, made factors, some with ordering, deleted “bad” values from future integer variables (i.e. got rid of “don’t know” and “refused” levels in them). But, generally, no major ideological changes.

Log10-transformed distribution of number of books, read in last 12 month, for the better view of the long-tailed distribution.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the

investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in

the dataset?

I’ve found three features, that positively correlated with the number of books read.

First is whether one has or doesn’t have e-reader. Respondents, who have e-readers tend to read more books (no causation!).

Second is income. Each next level of income has slightly higher median value of read books.

Third is educational level. Postgraduates, who doesn’t have degree are the most enthusiastic readers. Maybe it is due to preparing for the degree exam.

Concerning frequency reading. Owners of the e-book readers and tablet computers are tend to read electronic books more frequently. More, than 56% of respondents don’t read electronic books on computers and cell phones.

And even if somebody has a e-book reader, he or she still tend to read printed books.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features

(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Education level and income level are positivaly correlated, though age can be confounding variable. And older people have more cell phones, which are not smartphones.

More interesting is that among those, who have e-readers, 35% doesn’t read any electronic books during the last year.

Those, who have e-readers, tend to have tablet computers too.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

I believe that relation between income and number of books read is worth mentioning. Though it is not very strong relation, but the most interesting from all my findings.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the

investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of

looking at your feature(s) of interest?

Such features as income level and owning a special device (favourites from the previous section), for reading e-books, do a good job together. Higher income plus owning a device predict potent to reading higher number of books decently.

Also, I made a grouping by owned devices, and comes to quite interesting conclusions. More above (or below).

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

Among those, who hadn’t read anything those, who have at least one compact devise for reading (e-books reader or tablet) is the smallest group (among all numbers of books read), lagest part is those, who doesn’t have neither spesial e-books reader, nor tablet. People, who have non of possible devices (computer, cell phone, e-reader or tablet) appear only in the “0 books read” and “2 books read”.

It is quite visibly, than when we move to the larger amount of books read, groups, that owned at least one compact devise become lager and larger.

And there is two types of people, who read most (my friend)) - those who have both e-reader and tablet and those, who don’t have neither.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This is original distribution of books read. I want to show it, because it struck me, that 206 from 1005 people in sample didn’t read a one single book in the last year. General question was - why so many people don’t read? And what is the features of people, who read more and less?

Plot Two

Description Two

Here we can see first - that median numbers of books read increase with the increasing of income, and, second, that in the most income groups those, who has e-reader read, on average, more books.

Plot Three

Description Three

And here is some answer for the original example - those, who didn’t read for the most part don’t have a compact device for reading. Those, who have a tablet or e-books reader tend to read more.

I suppose, that around 100 mark a those people, who read, by their opinion “very many books”. We don’t know - it is true of exaggeration, but still - it can be true, so I decided to left this group. These people are either have two compact devices for reading, or none of those.

Reflection

Pew’s data set contain 1005 sets of answers (each set of answers = one respondent) about reading. Most of the variables in this data set are categorical, numerical variables is age - which, in fact, better in the bucketed form, so more or less categorical too. So I worked with one numerical variable, that imposes some restrictions on the form of graphs. Also, this set is not very handy for using modeling techniques. Nevertheless, I’ve found some quite interesting, but obvious associations. I suggested, that the age is correlated with the number of books read, and was surprised, that education level and income level are better predictors. And it is interesting, that those who read, still read printed books. Maybe, not environmental friendly, but e-book reader can’t give one satisfactory tactile sensation.

It can be interesting to investigate, how do the reading habits change with the coming of the e-reader devices to the market. For such research I need data sets like original for the different years. My suggestion is nowadays people can read more while travelling and are doing so.
